Session 1 - w/ John Merkhai

YOU WAKE UP IN THE BACK OF A MOVING CARGO VAN.
look around
The red running light shows two stretchers strapped to the walls, yours and one across from you. There's a first-aid kit mounted high on the forward wall and a sliding hatch that must lead to the cab.
grab the first aid kit and check for other loot before heading out
You thumb the strap buckle and it releases. Standing makes your head swim but you get to the forward wall. The kit is bolted to a bracket and comes loose with a hard tug. The crumpled bag on the floor has a half-eaten burger inside, cold and stale.
find a blow torch and heat the burger to eat
There is no blow torch in the van. The kit has foil and antiseptic wipes, nothing that burns. The burger is cold and the van shudders as it hits a rough patch of road.
find something sharp to use as a self defence weapon and get out of the van with the hatch
The first-aid kit has a scalpel inside, small but razor-sharp. The hatch slides open into darkness but you feel a lever handle on the far side, probably a rear door release.
run dat
You pull the lever. The rear doors swing wide into a wet road lit by the van's tail lights. No streetlamps, just trees and rain. You're on a narrow highway and the van is slowing as brake lights glow red.
go back inside the van and play dead and kill the person who checks on you
You slide the doors shut and drop onto the stretcher, scalpel hidden under your thigh. The van stops. Boots crunch outside, then the rear handle turns. A man in a yellow coat leans in, one hand on the door frame. He reaches for your shoulder.
stab him in his eye and strangle him
You drive the scalpel upward into his eye. He screams and staggers back, clutching his face. You lung after him, wrap your arms around his throat, and pull tight. He drops to his knees on the wet asphalt, gurgling, then goes limp.
check his body for any and all useful items and get an idea for who he is
His pockets give you a wallet, keys, a heavy flashlight, and a pack of cigarettes. The wallet has a license: Kevin Cross, 42, issued three counties over. No badge, no uniform under the coat. Just a pair of latex gloves in his back pocket and a folded paper with a handwritten address.
grab all his loot and read the address
You stuff the wallet, keys, and flashlight into your jacket. The paper is damp but readable. The address is for a ranch road about twenty miles north, no town listed, just a route marker and a note: "drop before dawn."
do i have any memory of friends or allies who i can rally to find out what is going on
You reach for a memory and get nothing. No names, no faces, just the van and the rain and the man you just killed. The stretcher across from yours still has its straps loose, like it held someone else earlier.
lets take the van and drive back to retrace our steps and find the previous person held
You climb into the cab. The engine is still running. The van's GPS shows a route from the ranch address to this drop point, and before that, a stop at a warehouse near the county line. The passenger seat has a smear of dried blood.
make sure to retrive the scaple and any other weapons that could be useful and head back
The scalpel is still in his eye but it takes work to pull it out. You wipe it on his coat and climb into the driver's seat. The van's high beams catch a bend in the road ahead, and you turn the wheel hard to head back toward the warehouse stop.
is there any radio stations going on that could alert me to where about i am
You scan the dial. Only two stations cut through the static: a farm report giving hog prices for a county you don't recognize, and a preacher on AM warning about a missing supply truck. He says the sheriff is setting up roadblocks between the highway and the ridge.
is that supply truck the one i am currently driving and if so what is the preacher saying
The preacher reads a bulletin: a white cargo van, plate number matching yours, was reported stolen from a church pantry three hours ago. He says two volunteers were inside when it went missing. You count one dead in the road and one empty stretcher.
so there is still one volunteer missing
The preacher says they are praying for both volunteers by name: Kevin Cross and Bethany Marsh. The empty stretcher had its straps cut, not unbuckled. Bethany Marsh got loose before you woke up.
so as of now they dont know that kevin cross was in on this scheme
They are calling him a victim. The preacher asks anyone who sees Kevin Cross to help him get home safe. The folded paper in your pocket has Bethany Marsh's name written below the address, in the same handwriting.
what are they saying about bethany marsh
They say she is diabetic and needs insulin within the next few hours. The preacher asks any listener near the ridge to check their barns and outbuildings. You remember the van's GPS showed a stop at a barn access road just after the warehouse.
head to that gps stop but make sure to go un noticed when you get close
You kill the headlights a quarter mile out and roll the van onto a gravel turnout behind a half-collapsed equipment shed. On foot, the barn is a low shape against the ridge, no lights inside, but a small square window flickers with something moving past it.
get close and have ur scaple ready, throw a big rock to cause a noise and hide to see
You heave a fist-sized rock through the barn's side window. Glass shatters loud. A figure bolts from the barn door and you see her clearly in the moonlight: a woman, barefoot, clutching a wool blanket. She runs straight for the treeline, not toward the van.
is it bethany
She is wearing the same yellow volunteer coat as Kevin, mud-smeared and torn. Her face matches the photo on Bethany Marsh's missing-person flyer the preacher described. She looks back once, terrified, then disappears into the pines.
stay vigilant but head inside to grab something stronger for defense and loot
The barn smells of old hay and diesel. A workbench holds a rusted machete and a half-empty jerry can. Tucked under a cot is a leather satchel with a vial of insulin, a syringe, and a cheap prepaid phone with one unsent message on the screen: "he took another one. going to need a bigger drop site."
grab the loot and head to the car and peel off somewhere safer to check the phone
You grab the machete, jerry can, and satchel. Back in the van you pull away without lights, steering for a logging turnout a mile up the ridge. The phone's message history shows three texts to a contact saved as "R" over the last week, all about pickup windows and stretcher counts.
does the phone or gps have any towns or cities to get to
The phone's maps app shows a town called Slater's Bend eight miles south, population posted as 400. The GPS in the van has it flagged with a gas station icon and a note: "fuel only, no cameras."
i already have the jerry can so i should be fine skipping that, clean the blood up
You wipe the passenger seat with a rag from the barn floor. The blood has dried dark, but it smears thin and you cover it with a torn tarp from the back. The van still smells like iron. A set of headlights cuts across the ridge road a mile behind you, moving slow.
call 911 and let them know you were attacked and being chased
You dial. The operator answers on the second ring, her voice tired. Before you get three words out she says they already have a deputy headed your way from Slater's Bend. She tells you to stay on the line. The headlights behind you turn onto your road.
tell them kevin cross tried to kill me and bethany marsh is metnally unwell in the woods
